<dl id="n32056c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n32" href="#n32056c">N32 (VI.B.23)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n32all.htm#n32056c"> 56(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> tadbhavas</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The Hindi form of Hindostani was invented simulataneously with Urdu prose by the teachers at Fort William. It was intended to be a Hindostani for the use of Hindus, and was derived from Urdu by ejecting all words of Persian or Arabic birth, and substituting for them words either borrowed from Sanskrit (<i>tatsamas</i>) or derived from the old primary Prakrit (<mark><i>tadbhavas</i></mark>). <small> &ldquo;HINDOSTANI&rdquo; <a name="EBHI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBHI"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 480(a) [Hindostani as a Lingua Franca]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
